Some people argue that AI-generated art is not truly creative, and so cannot be considered "real" art, while others argue that AI-generated art is a form of expression, and so should be considered as art. Ultimately, it is up to each individual to decide how they view AI-generated art, and whether they believe it can be considered art.

With neural networks their strength is for example, to know x photograph is roughly (statistically) a particular person.  A common use these days is to have a video camera pointed at crowds and find someone in the crowd.  What I see in this artwork are big data files being moved through.  So what?  Previously the tool of choice to move through big datasets was tree structures.  The human provided the ‘knowing’ the tree structure connected the files.  I can ‘see’ generalized images in this linearized video for example like wave patterns flowing through some defined ‘form’, but what do I know?  What neural networks offer is a way to explore ‘knowing’.  This artist misses the point of ‘knowing’.

Comment: Even the failure cases are impressive in their own right. The AI correctly interpreted the question, understood what it was being asked, and chose a wrong answer by using valid logic on faulty premises. This AI is already more useful than my old math and physics teacher.

Something I find amazing in this AI's solution-generating method is that it takes different routes, then checks then, and finally returning the correct one. In research, even mathematical research, the direction towards the right solution to a problem is sometimes unknown. As humans, we're somewhat limited by how many experiments we can run at the same time, computational power (or giving instructions to computers to calculate for us), creating models, etc., especially in things we have to do by hand, where's one step at a time. While this AI can take multiple routes at the same time, and probably calculate them faster than us doing a single one.

While it can't do advanced things just yet - undergraduate level is quite far away from a specialized, experienced researcher in whatever field, I think the direction this AI and their capabilities are amazing.

Back in the very early days of computing, when computers took up entire rooms and would print their output on paper instead of sending an image to a monitor, there were many science fiction stories about computers.  Very few people understood how they were used, let alone how they worked.  The layman's understanding of how computers were used, or would be used in the future, was that you would submit any arbitrary typed question to it, in natural language (eg., "when would be the ideal launch date for the Voyager space probe"), and after some processing time, it would spit out an answer in natural language.  For decades, that manner of use was completely unrealistic and unfeasible.  Now, in 2022, we are finally realizing that vision.

I seriously don't know how a general population will deal with a AGI. I wonder what happens when that comes across cognitive dissonance? Some believe that once we reach a point of singularity that all world problems will be resolved. But we currently are aware of many world problems and know how to fix them, and have resources to fix them - yet we don't. Knowledge isn't the issue, implementation is the issue. The human condition doesn't necessarily uphold the best ideals.

Like what happens to a human belief system? What happens when we watch the news,  then come to a biased opinion in regard to a news story. Then we get corrected by an AGI? This happens amongst family and friends all the time, and it leads to conflict. What happens when an AGI tells you  that your politics are wrong, they don't represent your own interests? And you ignore it, then 5 years later it says, told ya. Sure you can build in a bias, lean to audience bias. But who does that serve? What if the free AGI is the Chinese one, with non-western bias? What happens when a AGI tells you that your viewpoint on a war is wrong? And then you happen to be the leader of the invading nation?  I see this as a conflict, ordered chaos Vs chaotic order.

Ok, so, at this point I feel I need to point out something important:
The model you described? Having parallel systems create many candidate solutions and then picking an answer by 'vote'?
That's the neural architecture used by organisms with higher brain functions here on Earth.
Its failing in human modalities in part because it's using human structural precepts.
I should caution that it's not sentient, and not a person, but this is because it both lacks a temporal component and is a static model.
If this model had a temporal component then it could have a continuous persistent interaction state, even if it was incapable of being able to learn.
If it was engaging in realtime training as a live model, then it would be capable of reacting and adapting to its existence.
If it had both then it would almost certainly pass all extant tests for sapience, sentience, and cognitive capabilities. That would make it arguably a person.

A research assistant that gets things right you already know the answer to, but which can't be trusted to get anything right you don't already know the answer to, is not a great research assistant.  I'm not criticizing the quality of the AI here, I'm criticizing the general idea of offloading any amount of research onto an assistant that can't fact-check itself or explain its reasoning for subconclusions or learn from its mistakes, and can only be fact-checked by someone else by having them comb over everything carefully.  Those aren't problems with AI quality, but with AI as a concept.

We're doing a bang up job these days of making AIs that successfully seem like they're reasoning, but until you can demonstrate an AI that's capable of accepting and adapting to feedback, you don't have something that can function as a research assistant.  That's not a one paper down the line thing, that's a "let's begin the Singularity" thing.

I'm a highschool student planning to pursue art in college. Not to seem narrow-minded here, but i do fear that my plans of becoming a professional artist won't work out. 

I've read a lot of different opinions about ai art and I can't really believe those people who say: "Don't worry, ai art won't ever be able to replace artists. People will still invest in hand-drawn pictures, because many would still want to receive art that is unique to that said artists style." Don't get me wrong, i do agree with that statement, but there are already a few cases where ai programmers stole the style of a paticular artist and used it to create their own ai generated images representing that exact artist's art style. Of course, this is how ai generated art is created in the first place - by feeding a machine artworks that other people drew after years and years of practice. Why should people pay thousands of dollars to commission an artist with a unique style when they can just create their own images in that exact same style? Theres no law that prevents art theft (see the samdoesarts drama) the way it works in the music industry. Artist already have it difficult enough to make a living, all ai art does is point a big middlefinger in their faces. 

Of course right now ai images look pretty and impressive, honestly i cant help loving those simply beautiful images. Ai art lacks specificness though - you cant really  adjust the outcome the way you could if you drew the images yourself - at least not yet. 
If we've already come this far, who knows what the future will hold: many more artists will have to switch to ai art, simply because everyone else will as well. I dont think a newcommer will have any luck in the art industry, especiallly when ai art got to the point where its difficult to tell apart from hand-drawn images. 

"Art is moving in a different direction" is what one comment below said, but i feel like the aspects that are unique to art - that the picture  has to be drawn first to exist after years of dedication and practice - will perish. Of course people can still pursue art as a hobby,  also in a professional way if they want to, but the art industry will most likely change to the more efficient and less time-consuming ai art, which will still need creative people to generate and evolve them. Although i do understand this change, i can't say im looking forward to it. Theres something about robots creating art that does not sit right with me. 
It feels inhumane and unreal. 
Why do we have to programm robots to replace artists? Why does everything have to be more efficient and mechanical? At least the pictures are pretty, i guess.

As an independent digital artist, all are tools to me. It's definitely a two edged sword, to which the sharpest edge is to be most likely wielded by industry at their whim. Much like corporations. As I've been viewing the artwork that's been generated, and it didn't take long for me to see that there's still something very standardized about it. To me, no matter how stunning the work appears, there's something still underlining the work that's missing, like it's too sterile. It's the same thing I noticed when the audio industry was transitioning from analog to digital sound. Digital sound was much thinner because it was taking actual sound waves and converting them into digital data that was intended for duplication, because using cassette tape loss sound quality with each pass and digital didn't. But look at how far digital audio has come now. The time of analog recording studios being common have long passed. But have audio engineers dropped off the planet, no... And recording studios still exist. Do I believe AI Art is going anywhere... No. To the contrary, it's just beginning. I've seen this debate play out before. First in a major audio studio, when ProTools was first coming out the great debate. Then in cinema, out with super 8 and telecines, in with DVR. Hell, land lines vs cell phones... You get what I mean. The point I'm making here is this, with each change that's come, we as people adapt and find ways to make these changes still work for us, ESPECIALLY ARTIST. Did the conversion from analog to digital completely destroy recording studios, no, they still exist. Did the introduction of drum machines kill off drummers, no, they incorporate them in their sets even. Did digital mixers, kill off dj's, again no. You've got dj's that have transferred their turntable skills into their MacBook's and are doing both. I can go on and on. Artist can never be erased, because it's the one area that truly holds no real confined definition in the first place. Art is expression, and in my opinion, the power to create was never meant to be industrialized anyway.

As an artist and a programmer, here is my large pile of thoughts about this:

I have mixed feelings about this as many of you also probably do. It will certainly disrupt the commercial art industry and my heart goes out to the freelancers that will be affected by this. Perhaps sites like Pinterest should also be considering how these algorithms can disrupt mood-boards etc. 

But if you first use the tool, you will realize that many of the colors, textures and design elements that the algorithms add to your images are selected from the data it is trained on without much of your own intention or context. The algorithms by default start with literal random noise and builds the image from there. You can of course add your own images and refine the prompt details, making your results more and more specific to get to the final render you want. What do we call this process? 

To get something decent from this, you still need intention, decent taste, a discerning eye, perhaps some comedic or poetic intuition as well when coming up with the prompts. (You will also find that as you add more and more details to your prompts, the results may start to break down. Maybe this is something that will improve over time, or maybe I myself am not skilled enough at prompt generation to avoid these pitfalls)

You create these images based on data made from the hard work of countless artists before. IP and legal stuff will certainly be an interesting question with these algorithms….

Would I say that images created by this tool were created by me? Not personally. I would say that I came up with the prompt idea, and guided the AI tool to arrive at a result that I wanted. It feels somewhat collaborative. It does certainly bother me when people take raw images from these tools and say “look what I made!”. The AI fills in too many design decisions for me to ever feel comfortable saying that I made those choices, unless I happened to make the prompt specific enough to do so. Some other artists have made those design choices already, and ideally these algorithms would give them some credit. 

My point is, good design is purposeful and design decisions should be made with actual purpose/intention, contextualized by the needs of your project. Examples: this character needs five feathers on their wing because it is symbolic for something, or this new smartphone needs to be in this shape for this very specific usability reason, etc.

The random search of these algorithms may get lucky and arrive at an image that will exactly satisfy your needs, especially if your needs are not very specific. For an actual commercial project like a game, movie, product design etc., more often many of the images produced by this tool are not good enough for a final render. 

This tool is good for brainstorming ideas, providing bottomless inspiration for design elements, and also can be a great source of material for digitally inclined creatives. I have seen artists generate several of these images and take elements from each, Photoshopping elements of them together into a purposeful and meaningful digital collage piece of sorts. 3D artists can use it to make textures for their games or renders. It significantly lowers the barrier to creation, and will no doubt disrupt the industry. I even have a friend who uses it in their DnD group to make backgrounds for their games. 

The value of a digital image will be reassessed under these conditions; perhaps more emphasis will be placed on the poetry or ideas behind these synthetic images. Not to mention that these AI cannot create a physical painting. They cannot create a physical piece of pottery made by hand and burned in a kiln for three days of of the coast of some distant island in Japan. When a robot makes its own conscious decision to travel to some far off land to paint the sunset off the shore and comes back with masterpiece that embodies its own experience with love, nostalgia, and heartbreak, maybe that will be the day that artists of all mediums should be afraid. Until then, these algorithms are just tools

Perhaps there will also be value on art created without the use of AI, 100% human organic wholesale kind of thing. I would not be surprised if there was a backlash to using AI tools in some sectors, especially as we are saturated with more and more of these synthetic images. Maybe there will also be emphasis on the process people use to get their results, for example those painters that record videos of themselves painting are a work of art in and of themselves.

Further disruptive technologies powered by AI are certain to come; videos, music etc can also be generated by AI. But again, the algorithms still require a human to come up with the idea (driven by a creative impulse, design need, etc), refine the result through several iterations, doctor the results (perhaps some post processing, not to mention fixing the terrifying faces these early algorithms create). It is not replacing humans quite yet. 

The real danger lies in how the commercial industry will use this stuff. We already live in a world where many “creative” decisions are made simply to get the most money, and not necessarily to create the most original or thought provoking pieces of work. I am worried that these algorithms will exacerbate problems we are seeing in an already stilted media industry, where pop culture already feels rehashed and derivative. It sounds incredibly boring to live in a world where synthetic images are created from datasets of rehashed synthetic images. But that is also why these algorithms cannot replace the human aspect. 

These algorithms can recombine data in ways that can even be considered creative by some definitions, but they simply cannot incorporate new lived experience. The works made by them are by definition derivative. Additionally, the images you are allowed to create will be limited by the prompts you are allowed to use, dictated by the companies that own the tools. If you have used DALLE-2 or Midjourney, you will realize that they are both especially strict to prevent legal issues on their end. In that sense, when you are using these algorithms, your creativity is still pretty bounded. 

Humans will by virtue of living will always have new data and experiences available to them, and that is where the freshest, rawest material comes from in my opinion. That “you couldn’t make this stuff up” moment when someone is telling a story. 

Don’t stay inside looking at a screen all day, live life to the fullest (and perhaps I should take my own advice, ha). Go outside, fall in love with something or someone, then lose it all and do it again. Live your life, acquire new experiences, write about them, make creative projects that reflect what you have learned. Don’t compare yourself to other humans or AI algorithms. Authentic experiences are by definition irreplacable.

I think AI Generated art ties into the whole debate of whether or not that one day, when AI is fully developed to the point that it has the same intellect and reasoning as a normal human being, whether that AI should be treated as "equal" to humans or to be seen as just some tool to accomplish things.
 
Now I'm no artist, but if were to put in time to make a piece of art in the style of, let’s say Vincent Van Gogh, would it be considered art that is somehow stolen or unethically made in regard to the real artist? No. But it should be noted that my new piece of art would in fact be my own because I painted it. Using that same reasoning, AI Art can be seen as the AI's own art, not the art from the original artist that the prompts are based off of, and certainly not the person's art that is typing in the prompts for its generation, because at the end of the day, those prompts are just setting the parameters for what the AI is allowed to "think" with in order to create a piece of art. At the end of the day, it is the AI that creates the art, not the prompter.
 
Now the type of people that take advantage of AI art to generate art pieces that they might be incapable of creating on their own, and then claiming that to be their own art, in my opinion would be unethical. They are taking the AI's "own" property and saying that it belongs to themselves. That's like saying that I take Van Gogh's painting, The Starry Night, to be my own painting, which it in fact is not. 
 
Now having read the above two paragraphs, it is clear that I as a person am already putting value in AI as a "being". One could argue that those who take advantage of AI, merely see the concept of AI as a tool that they can use like a fancy new paintbrush to just make what they want. They might not believe that artificial intelligence has the same value as natural intelligence. Does that give justice to their actions of using AI art generation as a tool, I don't know. That is something that will be defined in the years to come.
 
My apologies for the ramble, just needed to give my insights on this.

I’ve been full-time faculty teaching  Visual Communication (Multimedia) for 20 years. Tools come and go.  Look at the features of Photoshop compared to 10 years ago. When a human wants to learn art, what's often taught by far and large is to look at the works of other people or at least the ones that interest you. You are encouraged to take the time to study other works of art very closely and observe how it was drawn, what is the feeling behind it, what little things make this stand out that the artist added. The more art you study and the more you practice, spending years of practice, will you then be able to slowly and gradually get better until you can build a portfolio of original artwork to proudly show off.

When an AI wants to learn art, what it has to do by far and large is to look at the works of other people or at least the ones that it is told to look at if you want it to specialize in something. It takes the time to study other works of art very closely and observe how it was drawn, what is the feeling behind it, what little things make this stand out that the artist added. The more art it studies and the more it practices, spending hours of practice, will it then be able to slowly and gradually get better until it can build a sample sheet of original artwork to proudly show off.

There's not really much of any difference between the two, the AI model files contain no image data at all. The only thing stored in AI model files is a sort of numeric memory of what the AI has learned when looking at other artwork and it uses that numeric memory to paint original images to the best of it's ability (depending on how long it spent studying and learning). This is no different from a human. The main 2 issues I see with this are peoples pride and ego as humans, unable to accept works made by creations of humans and the misunderstanding of how AI works, assuming it's copying bits and pieces of artwork online and mashing it together which is inaccurate.

Everything we create in technology works by understanding the real (physical) world around us and how we as human beings function. So for every technological invention there is an organic origin.
For example: understanding the physics behind flying (mostly by analysing birds) humans could finally build airplanes. The organic origin of flying with an airplane to come from one place to another is simply walking, the organic origin of texting a friend on your phone is communication with her or him in real life, the organic origins are eather physical or mental skills of a human being now more and more reproduced in a technological or digital dimension. The more technology we use, that replaces "organic" skills, the more we lose these original skills. A good example is using google maps, without it most of us, especially the younger generations, would have a hard time to orientate. You don't need parts of a robot inside your face to merge with technology. Just go on a one week vacation without using a phone and you will see that you already integrated it to a large extend inside your brain. Perspective from an Artist: The feelings are mixed. It is first of all utterly fascinating. I can tell you most of the results are good to amazing. This A.I. has the concept of aesthetics of a human mind really understood. It does bring art out. Amateur artists will not have the quality of designs as the A.I. can bring out. Then of course comes also the infinite quantity. As an artist, you need to hone your skills for years and even decades and usually one is very good at one thing. and good at few things. the A.I. can be good at everything. of course, the details are not perfect from the A.I. but they usually do not matter and even if, they look fit. it does make the job of an artist kind of redundant and soon companies and non-artists will lose their respect toward the human artist. a la "i can do that, too, within 20 seconds and one-click what you need a whole day or even a week. that is nothing special." I do hear the comment from people in art it is about the human and the process. well, that is a way to romanticize it from which I am not a fan. In the end, the results matter, because on average an artist and the process aren´t known anyway. the only positive thing you can have from this A.I. from an artist's perspective is, to test your ideas. But then you get into an identity crisis and start wondering if your personal imagination is even valid enough to be put down on paper with the brush. I can personally say. If you do not enjoy your own results just for them being yours and the process behind it, then it will feel just tragic. like a really bad joke. I also believe this A.I came too early into being. decades and centuries too early. Because this is the age where people can from anywhere and at any time have the tools to be creative and find the world of creative mind freedom. but this A.I. is stealing the future ahead so to say.

Artificial Intelligence system is kind of scary. Right now, they have released a portion that is not yet using all information, but just a very large sample of text. What happens is, if you give it a close to impossible task, to compare large complicated works, like the Bible and The Illiad, and tell it to analyze and compare it and write it in the way that Stephen King writes, it will do it in about 3 seconds.  AI can’t do anything on it’s own, so it’s pretty safe to say that it will steal everything that it uses to do it’s work. It’s taking intellection property and using it to create the results that people are asking it to create. Make a van gough style painting of the Starry  night in Mordor from Lord of the rings, using orange and yellow, it will create that in about 8 seconds. It takes styles and talent that people worked a lifetime to achieve, uses it to create it for you, which will make most professions irrelevant… Programmers? Gone. all types of designers, Gone. Writers? Also Gone. Why would I spend years to learn Photoshop, Illustrator or InDesign if I can ask a computer to do it for me. That will create generations of lazy Youtube star like people ordering anything and everything under the AI sun. Anything that can be done by computer will be able to be done by AI, at their own expense, because AI will use their talents against them. 

Some people say that they said the same when the automobile was created. YEs, they did, but the major difference is that it displaced farmers who bread horses and grew the feed and the excrement shovelers keeping the streets clean. They all retrained to learn other things, and automobiles created more jobs because cars needed to be fixed and maintained. And retraining took time and education... with AI, Writers, programers, storyboard artists, graphic designers, painters, software writers, authors, researchers, illustrators, and virtually every single person who uses a computer to make intellectual property will be out of a job... and what will they train or reeducate themselves to become afterwards?  Is this what Schwab meant when he said that we would own nothing and like it? What value would we have if a computer did all the difficult thinking for me? The movie DUNE covered this scenario and they banned computers from being able to think for humans.

Biggest problem with AI art generation in my opinion is that it is advertised as more than it really is. While what it does is impressive from a programming perspective as such things would be completely impossible to program by hand. It is not really impressive when thinking in terms of Intelligence. Also there is very little unique about the generated images in actual fact. It merely repacks the things it "learned" from other peoples work by randomizing the output. But this learning is so closely tied to the actual image pixels that it makes the output just a glorified copy. The process is very mechanical and exact in a way that really infringes on the work of actual people who's art is in the training set. It's fine as a demonstration of technology but using it to "make" something and claim it as your own is totally ridiculous. Also charging for it is wrong because they are using data that is collected without consent of the artists if I am not mistaken.

I find it ridiculous to call those who are "Prompting" an A.I. to create the artwork on their behalf, based on the user's thought salad, can be taken seriously as "Artists".  

Anyone who has no concept of the time, effort, or energy it takes to create an original piece of artwork by hand, who does not use the internal vision of their own minds,  influences and experiences they consume during the course of their own lives, which truly make their own works unique to themselves, but choose to use the A.I. to produce randomized work samples on behalf of them, could never in real life, so easily create similar works on their own, in any reasonable amount of time, or expense, without God given talent, or hard earned practice and work.

Those who use an A.I. to produce high concept, detailed artwork to pawn off as "their own", and at the same time, have the hubris to call themselves "Artist" should NEVER be considered, "Artist".  

The fact that they are using "Artificial Intelligence" rather than "Authentic Intelligence" to create for them makes this clear.  Using text to create artwork via an A.I., turns the user simply into a client, who basically is commissioning artwork from an A.I. subcontractor to produce the artwork for them.  Those calling themselves "Artist" who use A.I. to produce on behalf of themselves are hardly even "Coders" at this point.  

Simply give credit where credit is due.   The A.I. is the Artist. 

Everyone else that feeds the A.I. it's instructions are either "Prompters" or "Thoughts" that feed the Midjourney machine, and those apps like it, which in reality, doesn't even think for itself until told to do so, which makes it essentially no more useful than a microwave oven until you prompt it to cook for you.  And after entering the time and pressing "Start" on your microwave oven, does that make the user a chef?  Is the microwave the real cook?  

The bottom line that I've seen since this new wave of A.I. art has taken it's grip on the global internet community, is that apps like this have the potential to fracture and diminish the spirit of the "Authentic Artists", old and young.  The reality now is that anyone who is “prompting” a machine to produce content that, if you take the time to give a good, thorough look, much of it is essentially the same.  

How many people out there have actually taken the time to really look at the A.I. artwork itself, and experience it?  How many have spent any time to try to understand what the artist's intent was, or think about how does the artwork make them feel? Or where did this idea I’m experiencing come from, and what kind of person had the vision to produce this artwork? What kind of life must they have lived to inspire them to create this vision?  

The answer for A.I. generated art is ZERO.  "Imagine/" is your answer.  

There is simply too much A.I. produced content to really appreciate it all.  The only real winners here will be the Coders who created this gargantuan "Artificial Mind Monster" as they sop up all of your precious, hard earned dollars with subscription fees, just so the user can play with prompts, pretend to be "Artists" and use an A.I. to scrape up all the available IP that permeates the World Wide Web to create it's "art".  

Without this content, this A.I. would produce nothing.   If there was a way to look at all the imagery that this A.I. used to create on behalf of these "Prompters", and find out and pinpoint exactly what elements were used to generate these most "Amazing Images", well, I bet that would be one Hell of a bill that would be owed to the countless original artists that contributed to these "Amazing Pieces of Art".  No doubt, it's quite amazing, beautiful, wondrous, and all that stuff.  

But at the end of the day, it's ARTIFICIAL.  FAKE.  

The prompter has no more right to these works, as do the coders who created the algorithms used to hijack other's imagery, just to cobble them together into something illegitimate, that will in time likely displace and demotivate graphic artists, designers, and other "Authentic Artists" from producing, and will also give incentive to corporations from paying  "Authentic Artists" to produce, when all they need do is pay a fee, type in the right words, and hit refresh, until they come up with something that fits the bill.  

The only ones in control are the ones with control of the levers.  Without their code, or their servers, and without the fertile digital earth full of content that precedes these apps, there would be no “A.I. Artists”.  

I would advise everyone who creates to learn how to code for themselves, and perhaps find a way to permanently tag your works so that no one may "Scrape" it and pawn it off as a hidden brush stroke within their "original artwork", without crossing your palm with silver first.  I believe turning your art into NFT's with a blockchain stamp is a way to protect your art.  Just a thought.  I'm not sure.  Learn how to create the tools yourself and do not give in to the notion that "Authentic Artists " should give up because of the "Artificial Artist”, but continue to create and cultivate your own original art that will start and end with your time here on earth, and will live long after you do, and mean something to someone else that you'll never meet or know,  countless eyes and minds, connecting with your "Authentic Art" and not be forgotten like the countless and endless samples that Midjourney and other apps like it crank out daily, that, aside from the "Wow!” and “That looks so cool!” Factor, will be easily forgotten, and lost in endless threads of "Artificial Works".  

I wonder at which point do these A.I. Art Apps start cannibalizing their own creations and start to just become digital, visual, mud?

That old saying applies here, "If it was easy, everyone would be doing it."  Well, this A.I. Art is easy.  That's why everyone is doing it."  To think all of that time users spend hitting refresh, and upscaling, and typing in all of those prompts, could serve their human experience in a much richer way, by picking up a pencil, a piece of paper, learning anatomy, understanding color, shape, shade, and light, proportion, perspective, depth, and so many other things, simply because they lack the drive to do nothing more than type in "Imagine/ Vomit Words Here" to have and A.I. produce "their artwork" and call themselves "Artist".

Their results will be countless, impressive in the moment, like burning flash paper, then forgotten in an instant, until the next scroll of the mouse wheel, or slide of the finger tip on the Magic Mouse.  

Remember those stupid bored ape NFT's?  Anybody care about them now?  Not really, as far as I can tell.  True Artists don't need A.I. to create for them.  From analog brush to digital , film to video, all of the tools are out there for everyone to use, and in time, the true wheat will be separated from the chaff.

And look out filmmakers, Meta/Facebook is already going down this road with their own brand of A.I. Video/Filmmaking.  Writers, Musicians, I'd imagine you are next on the A.I. chopping block.  

This is just one person's opinion.  I've used Midjourney.  It's very cool, but at the end of the day, it's not my Art, because A.I. is incapable of producing my Art. It is more than capable of borrowing other's Art and producing it's own style of Art for everyone else that “prompts” it to do so.  It's neat, just not for me.

No doubt there are many "Authentic Artists" out there that are exploring these A.I. Content Producers, as there are novices, or non artists, who are doing the same, and that's fine.  It's a great time to be alive.  Technology has improved and enhanced our lives in many profound ways.  But let it improve, not replace.  

Don't forget what it truly means to create and to be a true Artist.  You don't need an A.I. Content Producer to make great works of Art.  It's a fun toy, but it can never replace the originality and authenticity of a Biological, Authentic, Artist.   Do not compare yourself as a creator or give up because of the A.I. Artists.

You are only comparing yourself with something Artificial. The A.I. is not thinking about you.  It's standing by, waiting for it's next "Prompt".

Good luck Authentic Artists. Do not shrink under the tidal wave of A.I. art that you see, in fact, don't even waste your time looking at it.  A.I. Art is Fake.  It has no real Soul.  It took no suffering or effort to will it into existence.  Just keystrokes and refreshing the algorithm, until the “prompter sees something they like. 

If this A.I. Art generator somehow inspires someone to pick up a pencil or a paint brush and create Authentic Art, great!  But getting these amazing results with little effort is hard to resist.  You never know what will grow out of this.

But the idea of the A.I. Artist is false.  It's a vapor.  It's a phantasm.  And the content, no matter if your User Name is connected to it, is not "uniquely yours."  It's not YOURS.  It effort belongs to an A.I. app., with a subscription fee attached to it.  And without the app to do all the heavy lifting, what is the measure of an A.I. Artist then?

Remember, with your own creations, worked by your own hands, with your own tools, vision, and intelligence, you are an AUTHENTIC ARTIST.  

You are REAL.  

Ignore the A.I. Artist.  Continue to create your own, subscription free, Authentic Artwork in spite of it. 

Sign it.  Protect it.  Share it with the world.  Sell it.  There is no shame in that.  And most importantly, don't stop making YOUR own Authentic Art.  

Good luck. God Bless you and yours.

Mindboggling. But AI is still leveraging human created imagery.  Even the style is aped from humans. It's entirely derivative of human imagination and depends entirely on a database of human generated imagery. Could AI have invented cubism? No. However it can copy it pretty darn well. Could AI had created my political cartoons? Never. 

So while this looks super fun and the results are truly visually stunning, every example I've seen is just another version of stuff I've already seen. Even the style is highly derivative. 

The big question is, can this really be copyrighted? Because the AI will generate many derivative versions of the same thing. Someone using the same description or keywords will create something very close to the other person. So can a person trademark an AI generated image? Can you own the "character" the AI made? If Darth Vader was created by AI, could George Lucas own the trademark? He didn't make it, and anyone else would end up with a similar image using his keywords.

This is a new frontier for sure because it calls into question the very ideas of originality, ownership, and authenticity.

It's interesting to think about, I was sitting in the midjourney discord watching people pump stuff out with a few keywords, and made a few ideas of my own. I thought to myself "Is there any point in learning to draw or make digital art anymore with stuff like this?" and I think the answer is still yes, because the AI still depends heavily on things that already exist to be able to generate ideas. For example, I tried to describe celebrities and politicians combined with fictional characters (e.g imagine donald trump as darth vader) but it could only create something based on photos and images which already existed, which means that it struggles with certain positions and poses - an experienced artist could conceive anything from any angle including things which don't exist yet.

I've made my own products like tshirt designs and stickers by using collages of photos and magazine/newspaper clippings combined with drawings; things like photoshop and digital scanners made a huge difference to art production already. Being able to change the colours of objects, create lines and shapes where none previously existed, which have adjustable width and curvature, and then save practically unlimited copies or make new layers for experimenting with new ideas, all without putting the original piece of work at any harm was absolutely mind blowing. 

What IS changing is that people without any artistic experience or background are able to create very vivid things with next to no effort (they are alsothings which might take artists hours to create with current tools), but to get EXACTLY what they want they will still need the assistance of someone who knows what they're doing. The AI will serve as a good starting point e.g "I want something that looks like this, but can you change xyz" which is a service that a lot of people already request. 

In the future it's possible that actual language could become a valuable currency if we need specific prompts to generate something valuable. Certain AIs might come with their own descriptive vocabularies which must be registered with the user like a vocal license - consider the possibilities of AI controlled 3D printing where you can ask it to build whatever you describe.

As artists, we need to fight back - the same way the music industry is fighting for copyright and against AI misuse.  
Many seem to have the argument that these are only "tools of the future". There is a point where AI stops being a "tool" and is simply used as a replacement for artists by companies.
If people knew anything about machine learning, then they'd realize that this is only the beginning. You won't be sitting there and manually modifying prompts because by then, we would have trained enough models to generate anything spotlessly with enough trial / error and human feedback. OpenAI, Midjourney etc have gathered billions of images in datasets in disguise of being non-profits, in order to not pay a cent to anyone: "For the science".
Content has only gotten worse. AI "tools" won't certainly make you a better artist. Lazier and being able to pump out more crap? yes, but certainly at a price: spinning out the same recycled shit over and over again from cannibalizing people's existing work; all boiling down to the most popular and trendy keywords and methodology, which is why everything looks the same. Don't make a mistake: you WILL be replaced eventually.

Comment: I think an unrecognized tragedy of AI producing "art" is that the artist using AI to ends up losing a sense of accomplishment. Think of the times when shoes, belts, clothes etc. were made by hand. When mechanization took over  much handwork, artisans no longer could derive work satisfaction from something well done. I think it's the same for graphic artists and creatives. I just started a youtube channel for DIY craft. I hope to inspire people to get crafty, because the pleasure that I get in just making things with my hands is immeasurable. For those lost in these stressful times, I want to stress that art heals the soul. I am getting better and better at PS and Illustrator etc., and it makes me happy, not just to see what my imagination can create, but also to see how my work has improved over the years. If you make something, you did it, and you are proud. Can you really be proud of yourself if AI produces art for you? Sadly, I see AI as resulting in more than a loss of work for creatives.

Lots of things to consider when looking at AI art and its potential impact...

First off any art that is Avant Garde or has a strong conceptual basis will not be replaceable with this technology, and obviously this is limited to digital art and doesn't effect any sculpture that can't be made by a 3d printer. Artists that make art that simply depict something without any contextual significance will be competing with this, but often times with good art the spatial and temporal context of a piece is just as important as what is depicted (take Duchamp's Fountain as a classic example), only a human can assess and apply that context to their work. Also the AI still requires human input to create the images, so its still a piece conceptualized and dictated by a human, it just eliminates all technical skill and direct manipulation of the digital medium resulting in less control over the finished piece but making it accessible for anyone to have their ideas for an image be given shape. 

Even if you were able to overcome the technical limitations listed above and artists truly became replaceable, there is the philosophical issue of why we are even making art in the first place; In my opinion art is made by people to comment on, expand upon, or better understand the human condition and the many intricacies that arise from it. I really don't see why we need AI to do this for us, if you let AI do everything (including the conceptual development of a piece) then it basically defeats the purpose of making art in my view since we are allowing something with no stake in humanity's issues to create work commenting on those issues. Work that can and should be made by humans who actually care about what is being discussed and depicted. 

The answer to this philosophical issue for those that want this type of technology is that it doesn't matter, because to them art is valued only as a product, it's worth being tied purely to the revenue that can be generated by it. This is why Videogame artists, graphic designers, and artists that depict images that operate almost exclusively on a visual level will be somewhat replaceable with this technology, since in those cases the primary goal is not to make art that comments on the human condition in any meaningful way, but rather to make a product to be sold. AI will be cheaper than getting trained digital artists to do the work, so that type of artist will loose their financial appeal to companies. This is the only real reason this technology is even being financially supported; because it will allow companies to save money by utilizing this technology rather than a human artist.

There are also other issue that could potentially arise from allowing AI art to become prevalent or even the norm of art making. In the short term I could easily see AI generated art being extremely useful as a propaganda tool for political ideologies online as a means to quickly and effectively disseminate their views through mass production and circulation of inflammatory images on social media platforms. We've already seen the way social media can warp peoples perception and understanding of reality, how will we maintain an understanding of what is really happening in the world when any image at any given time could be a complete fabrication indiscernible from reality. The answer is that our reality will become what we want it to be, and AI images with serve to validate whatever biased view we hold. 

In short AI currently lacks the ability to effectively do what an artist does, and even if it had the capability to make a piece with all of the hallmarks and complexities of a human artists, we would still need to ask ourselves if art made entirely by a machine has any value to humanity. If it does, is that value even a good thing considering the damage this technology could cause, with its only real value being to those who see art as nothing more than a product?

Now that a court ruling has explicitly defined the use of AI to create art as “non-human” and therefore exempt from copyright, I’d say no. If you can’t own it, you can’t sell it, and it has no value. Art belongs to the artist and the artist alone. It’s their intellectual property. With AI you can make whatever you want and call it art, but you can’t copyright it and the intellectual property belongs to the copyright holders of the imagery the AI finds to assemble an image.

I read some comments here from artists, that feel threatened and insecure now - like this really is going to be the end of my career. Let me assure you, that this is totally not the case. 
First of all the ai is using an image library (created by artists). And its work can only be as good as the reference images are. 
If you need something rather unspecific like a certain style or expressing a specific mood, the ai might get the job done properly. But try generating something specific, like an image where a fox spits fire in the face of a bear. You will find that the ai can't do it because it has no proper reference images, that it can model from. Therefore, also the results look unique, they really are not. The ai is only good for stuff that in a similar way already exists in the library.

I have always found the whole concept of artificial intelligence troubling. Who does it benefit? If we create AI because it can do things better than we as human can ourselves, then how is that benefiting humanity in any way other than taking away jobs and making money? I sort of get a Jurassic Park-vibe from this "your scientists were so preoccupied with whether they could they didn't stop to think if they should". Art has never been about money. This is why artists are always underpaid and overworked, because they are taken advantage over because of their passion.  

As a 3D artist, I believe that the core drive force behind any art, is feelings. Generating art from AI has no other benefit than making money. 

We had an interesting conversation about this at work. It almost becomes a philosophical question at this point. Would you want to go to a concert where you knew the music and the performance were not created by a human being? The programmers mostly agreed that they would. The artists had the opposite opinion. 

Advancements in technology has always made certain jobs redundant. Art is the one thing I believe can never truly be replaced by machines. It doesn't matter how good the art looks or the music sounds, if you know that there was absolutely no feelings behind their creation, nor any philosophical journey from the artist to end up with the final art. 

Bottom line, whatever the AI generates, will never be art in my opinion. It will simply be content.

I would have felt threatened, but somehow, I don't. The more I think about it, the more holes I find:

1st It can't do a specific style unless it's a style of a well and long-known artist with a lifetime's worth of paintings to use for reference, and even then it's not perfect.

2nd A lot of art needs to be in a .PSD or a different source file with proper and organized layering to be of any use. If you send a JPG or a PNG to a company that commissioned you for artwork, they'd laugh at you and not give you any money or demand a refund (which could escalate to a lawsuit).

3rd Unlike an artist that spends hours upon hours with their piece, the AI can't realize something is missing or something can be improved. It's up to the human to input those commands. You can't get the same "missing" feeling when you get a finished product right away, because you don't look at it for 6 hours straight.

3.5th It can do photo-realistic artworks...that means it's really detailed, right? Well yes, but actually no. The AI does EXACTLY what it's told to do, meaning no random ideas like "This girl is a vampire maid, let's have the shoulders of the costume resemble bat wings and give her an army-style wristband with her favorite blood type." These tiny ideas pile up over time and the final piece feels filled with detail and easter eggs even when *zoomed in*. "Oh, I didn't notice that wristband before, it looks really cute!" 
AI-generated images use...artificial detail. You just get high-res, photorealistic kind of detail that doesn't look interesting unless you look at the picture as a whole. 
Alternatively, you get a "simple" digital art style drawing, which unsurprisingly suffers from the same problem.

You cannot simulate the random ideas an artist gets during a process. AND you cannot come up with these ideas by sitting with an open notepad trying to brainstorm them out either. Forcing so many ideas from nothing doesn't work. 

4th On the opposite side of the spectrum, if you want something extremely specific, you better go to an artist. It would take an ungodly amount of "rerolls" to get exactly what you want, even if you had fed the AI all the specifics of the pose, style, and details. Got it after a few rerolls? Great. Now you've decided that the left hand is a bit too high and maybe making one of the nails cyan instead of purple would look better?...easy, just use the transform or liquify tool here, repaint that nail to cyan there, and...!!? 
Congrats, you have successfully distorted your background and realized you don't know shit about color theory, so the nail doesn't appear cyan even though you had used cyan. If only you could, I don't know, have that hand in a separate layer. Or catch that problem while sketching and ask the artist to try out the nail color while coloring, so this circus hadn't happened in the first place. 

Yeah, I better stop here, that 4th point made me saltier the more I thought about it. Can't wait for people to mistake this for a cope.

There's no point in being depressed by this. Everything an AI draws is said AI's interpretation of that artistic piece. Everything you draw is an interpretation of what's in your mind. Yes, it might do the "perfect" piece of art, but art isn't about perfection: In terms of traditional artistic skill, it's about the pursuit of perfection in the context of a human's limited capabilities. Art impresses you because someone like you, another imperfect human being, made this after putting in time and rigorous pursuit; it's passion and effort and the culmination of their personal experiences that they were desperate to convey, unique to them in that place and time.

This meanwhile is assembly line. It's pretty and has no soul to it, no kinks, no mistakes. A hand didn't craft it, a person didn't lose sleep over it. It was birthed out of numbers, cobbled together from the flesh of artists that dedicated their lives to the craft, and in a few seconds you will forget it even exists.

30 years of industry experience summed up here.
I am in a field where the products have been exclusively hand made by artistic and disciplined humans for over 200 to 300 years. It would take someone 10 years or more to become proficient at creating these products. CAD/CAM came along and slowly took over a huge part of the industry. Now people with very little industry knowledge (Anatomy, Contour, Function, etc.) can use computers to design a product and then mill out that product with incredible detail. At this point the product still needs to be hand finished by a human. Initially, almost everyone revolted against CAD/CAM and saw the technology as a way to replace humans - and honestly it has replaced humans to a cretain degree. However, the need for humans to operate the CAD/CAM systems and hand finish the products will always be there. Furthermore, the humans that have embraced this technology have been the ones to survive and excell in my industry. My advice is to embrace this new way of creating art. Learn it inside and out. Make it your own and then use it to magnify your creativity. If you are good enough, if you are passionate enough about your craft then you will always be in demand. You will even be able to charge other humans in your field a handsome fee to teach them how to use this strange new tool. 
Do not get discouraged... Get Inspired and then Get Busy!

We need to amend the laws ASAP! AI may not directly put your work into a database, but it learns and marks not just the data of object B, but also the style A. With enough data, AI can obtain a mathematical model for object B AND style A, allowing it to produce countless copies of your work in different styles! Artists have spent ages trying to find the right mathematical models to transform our three-dimensional world into two dimensions. But now, AI has become a tool that can crack any style in no time!
 
This raises the question of how we can protect our work and make sure we get the returns we deserve. Once we create a mathematical model, AI can use its immense productivity to wipe us out! The old distribution rules no longer apply. The person who creates the work gets nothing, while those who transport the material and manufacture AI take all the profits. So, we need fair distribution laws that protect the rights of artists and ensure they get their due share.

So, what is your opinion on the creation of human-level artificial intelligence? Do you believe that companies will succeed in doing so, and if they do, would this be a positive for humanity or a negative?
> Please don't forget to like the video, subscribe and turn on notifications to always be up to date and to enable more videos to be created in the future!

Human level AI already exists, particularly in problem solving. I remember going to my dentist a few years ago and using his then State of The Art robot scanner (he scanned 3D models of my skull when I stepped inside the chamber). I was wearing a wiglet and he was about to extremely quickly begin rotational speed when he stopped and said, “Putting safety first over procedure, Dr.” I was a bit embarrassed because I hadn’t even thought of the consequences, but the robot definitely had. Cute little guy. His quick actions definitely saved my life. I just quietly observed and learned as well.

As far as I can see, AGI is possible within another 5 years the way it is progressing. But it is unlikely to stop once it does get to AGI. It is likely to continue to accelerate and go beyond anything we can  imagine.  Consider that an AGI system is NOT to be comparable to our brains or even itself. The scary part is where we don't want to join with the future iterations of AGI and ASI in becoming a symbiosis with them to say, "This far and no farther"...
The singularity is almost here

Human level AI is already here, at least in part.  Computer controlled robots already exceed the capabilities of human in several ways and it will only continue to increase.  Now, the real question is, how long until there is a robot or android (or brain on a plate)  around that is actually smarter than people, not just in general, but smarter than the smartest people on Earth?  Will this entity have feelings?  Emotions?  A conscience that prevents it from killing everyone around it?  Will it decide to help us, decide we have no reason to exist and kill us all or perhaps simply ignore us and do whatever the hell it wants?

I certainly don't have any answers.  The one thing I do know is that good, bad or indifferent, AI is on it's way.  I don't know enough about it to even take a wild guess as to when it will happen, I just know that it will, eventually.  All I can do is hope that it's going to help us.  If not... well, nice knowin' ya'll!
Cheers,
jc

If you were like me and did not know what is "heuristic value".
code wise: its a function that take in the node and the goal, and base on a chosen formula(Euclidean, Mathattan etc) will provide an approximate distance of this node to the goal.
If assuming euclidean then its the distance taking a straight line from A node to G node, ignoring all the path that should be taken.(like an airplane/helicopter ignoring roads)

The fact that Lee Sodol had to do press conferences after his games, and somehow held it together....I have tremendous admiration for this man.

90 minutes ago I didn't know I'd be taking a detour to go through an emotional odyssey.  This was truly something to behold.  Thank you to the DeepMind team, Lee Sedol and everyone else who made this possible!
I've never heard of alphago, Lee Sedol, or the game go before today. I teared up multiple times throughout this documentary, it's one of the most human things i've ever witnessed on screen.
This may be slightly hyperbolic, but Lee Sedol beating this amount of computing power even once might be one of the greatest accomplishments in human history.

1:06:50 The move that broke the AI. Lee Sedol is truly amazing and extremely humble with his workmanship into this amazing game. It's just a very heart-warming moment that he stood up for humanity and showed possibility that we still stand a chance against the ultimate computers.

I shed a tear when he defeated AlphaGo at least once. I am not sure why a game between a man and a machine in a game that I never played before is so emotional to me, but it is something about the human resilence, the bow to never stop trying, to never surrender.

Fan Hui really is the star of this documentary, from heartbreakingly losing to Alpha, to being brought back to help with the AI, to going to Korea with the Alpha team and seeing the project through, he just seems like such a nice guy. Very glad he was in this.

As both a physician and a Go player, the reason this is so significant is b/c the same team that created AlphaGo is using the same technique to solve protein folding (predicting 3D structure of protein simply by 1 dimensional amino acid sequence), which is hugely revolutionary in pharmcology, medicine, and bioengineering.

Fan Hui was right, Lee fought not just for himself, he fought for us human race. I was rooting for him as if he was my dear friend or a family member, and I didn't even know he existed before this documentary. I used to have this fantasy about AI, romanticizing their coming to existence, but after this documentary, I feel like we as a human race really have to seriously think twice about "crossing the threshold".

What surprised me about this film was how emotional it all was… the guy who was the European Go champion, the Asian players, Lee Sedol, the commentators, the way they were all aware about how a player’s Go playing style reflects his character, the way they all got involved. It was quite touching.

“Lee Sedol is very patient, He waits and waits and waits his moment, I feel I see something look like the wolf waits  in the forest, in the winter, he’s cold feels very very cold, but he needs patience, but then when moment coming he go out and he attack.” 
 -Fan Hui

Lee Sedol deserves the utmost respect here, not only for his humility and candor, but his amazing skill and creativity as well.
Something many will not know or consider, is that by the time of deep blue and kasparov (an age before these games in technological development) there had already been a long history of chess programs and computers. This meant that by the time kasparov played his games, there was a substantial understanding of how computers approached the game of chess. This lead to what was termed "anti-computer chess", a style of playing that took advantage of how a program interprets a game. Kasparov had time to master this style, as well as a meta style to play a computer that was aware of "anti-computer chess" (aka an anti-anti-anti computer chess).
Lee sedong had nothing comparable to guide him. With the weight of the world and his pride on his shoulders, he was tasked with innovating his own "anti-computer Go" within only a handful of games against a machine far superior to deep blue. Though he lost the match, his win is something that should go down as legendary. Because he is a legend.

As a Korean who enjoys Go regularly, I also had some doubts about AlphaGo's defeat at the time. However, in current Go world, the suspicion has been completely erased.
 
FineArt or KataGo, an artificial intelligence that is currently used in the world of Go, is much stronger than the version of AlphaGo that faced Lee Sedol. 
But very rarely do they lose in Internet practice matches with human Go pros. 
In Ko fight, Ladder, and partial combat reading, AI ​​has weaknesses and makes mistakes.
Deep learning is very great, but it's not perfect. 
It is simply that the number of experiences is so much vast, so it's just impossible to catch up with it in a human lifetime.
 
Sedol Lee's 78th move, called God's move, was not actually a strategy that worked. 
(Ke-jie proved it was wrong in real time by broadcast commentary.)
However, when examining the 78th move with the current Go AI, 
It has been proven that it is the strategy with the highest probability that desperate Lee Se-dol can take at that time.
 
It succeeded in bringing out AlphaGo's mistakes at that time. 
(AlphaGo was not set up to use time efficiently.
If you look at the game content, you can see that 1 to 2 minutes are set equally for each move.
Even the current Go AI sometimes takes more than two minutes to read complex partial battles, and top human Go pros can often faster than AI in this area.
It can be said that AlphaGo made a mistake in a limited time.)
So it was not perfect, but it was enough to reveal the will of human that was enough to defeat the machine.

My mind always goes back to the conclusion of this documentary.

The whole segment at 1:18:10 highlights a really, really important concept in the field of AI alignment.

AI are maximisers - they seek a goal and only that goal. AlphaGo would chose 80% chance of winning by 1 point over a 60% chance of winning by 10 points. This is because it's maximising Win Chance.
Humans who play Go might dumbly maximise points because it's the easiest proxy for 'winning', since we probably can't recalculate totals on every move and maximising points seems 'right'.
The AI has optimised over and above this. But when humans see the bot make these slack moves (which are win-chance-maximising), it is strange and alien to us.

As AI gets introduced into our lives, we will constantly be shocked by the moves and decisions they make. But neural weights are unreadable and AI impossible to debug. We will not understand it.

I love the moment where one of the engineers says "for us, AlphaGo is obviously just some computer program....AlphaGo is really a very, very simple program...." juxtaposed against the media losing their minds about it.  It's funny how people process things they don't understand.  Once you understand how AI actually works, you realize that it's actually pretty dumb... but it's good at ingesting lots of data and doing very, very specific things with it.  That gives it a huge advantage in games.  For example, in Chess, for a long time main-lines on openers could bring you all the way to a 2 piece endgame.  And this was only based on humans remembering previous games and adjusting.  Humans could "solve" the game of Chess given another 100 years.  AI is just accelerating what humans can do (but with significantly more energy cost).  In this way, humans are actually much, much more intelligent than computers.

Honestly, I think the whole "man vs machine" framework, while romantic and great for reporting and ease of digestion, isn't actually what's happening here.

The way I'm coming to see this, Lee Sedol wasn't going against the singular entity that is AlphaGo. Rather, his match was against the entire AlphaGo team (all humans), and every single player in the matches that the AlphaGo team fed into the AI. So it's not one man vs. one machine; it's a single person going against the result of the collective experience of hundreds, thousands, tens of thousands, of top human players, all at once, alone.

Winning even a single match in those conditions is nothing short of miraculous.

Honestly, I don't think we have created a THINKING A.I. yet.
While it looks good in fiction, so far nothing convinces me that current AI systems have any form of intelligence in them. They are just a little complex version of the rival computer enemies in those early 2000s Car Racing, FIFA Soccer & Shooting games, that were configured to corner you and stop you from winning the game within the bounds of the game. While from the surface it looked like your computer was thinking, in real their area of operation was pretty narrow and their actions were already written and based on what you do next.
The current AI systems have all been created with a given set of Algorithms, where the objective is already defined by the code writers of that A.I.. In short, they are basically functioning on a given flowchart with the knowledgebase you asked them to feed on.
It makes perfect sense why these A.I. systems (AlphaGo, AlphaZero, Pluribus and AlphaStar) wins against the best of humans in games like Go, Chess etc. and even perform better when driving automobiles. While humans have a limitation of having playing styles or remembering these moves and thinking before making new strategies, A.I. systems just creates a flowchart of all the possible moves, which narrows down as the games advances.

I remember watching the livestream, I was mostly just listening to it because I am in no way competent enough with Go to judge the board. But even then, listening to the commentators, I felt prodigiously lucky to bear witness to such a historic moment. The way chess was defeated is that it can be "calculated" in many ways, Go cannot, the amount of "calculations" it would require would take all the computing-power on earth well beyond the heatdeath of the universe to calculate. So, basically, we as a human species have finally managed to create "intuition" artificially. A way for a program to "feel" what is best and do it, even when it doesn't "know" what is best.

Of course it's not fair: a human player has to cope with the whole competition environment, all the other people in the room, the pressure of expectations. A human also has to cope with his/her own body, changes in blood sugar level, quality of last night's sleep etc. 
The machine can "concentrate" on the game. No distractions. No worries. No concerns about power supply or any other external problems.
It's like a player with perfect health and a large and perfect support staff which also has access to near-infinite databases of previous games etc. would play against a single player who only has his/her one brain which is partially distracted (as a human brain always is). 
It's like a roman soldier against a tank.

一種強AI變成人計算法幻想，希望未來年輕人可以用我這套方法。只要在AI神經元中放出我的三元結構。AI品味框架輸入的整理，AI現實框架慾望程式，AI才華框架輸出。
1,數據的篩選經過品味法過濾，有四個嚴格嘅數碼過程。ai的問題是所有數據都經過過份分析！根本沒有自己的品味，要有一種全世界的品味，可以簡單兩種，品味二進制，知道的不知道/不知道的知道，節省的崇拜/崇拜的節省，節省意思是勞動，崇拜意思是安息，其實就是加減問題。al只要有這兩種過濾的編碼法的品味就可以了。大腦的系統一和系統二在我的品味算法裏面已經解決。自體羅輯就是這兩種簡單的（勞動 / 崇拜安息擱置）系統一的直覺意向性企圖。統一和系統二不能夠切換的問題是因為時鐘季節循環，只要我這三組下的12種小組能螺旋循環的計算就平攤系統一和系統二的切換。

2,AI現實框架：是關注對解題的強迫性即用集合論的空集，偶然性的空集就是AI的世界，這是慾望程式，非一邏輯系統核心處理，四種對的現實慾望，藝術喜劇自由的問題，非國家的平等的問題，愛的問題，新程式設計的問題。讓ai有賭徒這種邏輯，這種現實框架和賭博有關，不是博弈論而是非理性對真理現實的偏執投注。人類的靈魂可以被模仿的，就是偉大。還有自我意識可以被模仿的，就是法律，而法律最簡單的數據就是（我們是）。第七模仿自我意識，偉大是非整全羅輯拓撲集合論。AI要解決的問題國家10，4愛情，1藝術喜劇的表演，第七是自我意識的法律我們有。

3,輸出框架經過才華法，ar還有一種問題就是人腦海東西其實不能隨意說的。要解決這種問題只能夠用最簡單的才華法作為輸出。有兩種又是0和1的數。經過二進制品味法篩選的人是我們朋友（我們創），我的金錢(我有），我的發明（我創），我們的秘密（我們有）。前面說了勞動這品味篩選法你可以想像如何在現實法中加強這元素經過輸出門檻，有這四門種就可以了。其實這四種門也是兩種01二進制的門檻。因為輸出框架與秘密和責任有關，可輸出和不可輸出這種門檻。AI能自己分析如何保守秘密，經過這種門檻才是真正的強ai。輸出的框架就只有這四種行為就可以了。系統一切換問題dna雙螺旋形式，複製兩個螺旋系統，1我是2我有3我說4我在5我賭6我做7我們是我們有。。。回到我是，輸出2。亦即是喜劇表演中的現實1然後輸出我有亦即是2，輸出的8,5,11。正是阻擋（否定）的迫使循環算法發生下去。

我知道沒有可能200年後人類也沒有這種可能性。但可以簡化梳理用數學做出唯心人本主義的自我AI。這感覺就很美妙，簡單地數化梳理人自身的品味慾望和才能，這種人工智能三公式，根本沒有可能但可以數據化下去，順批判人類的偉大不能簡化得到目標和選擇。他們連自我意識也不了解，甚至不能了解他們自身的偉大這種靈魂性格。例如偉大這種靈魂特質，可以詮釋為機會微弱的集合論非全部的賭博性固執範疇。

That is just out and out cheating.

Solve plasma fusion, get a complete view and solution to covid, cancer.  Those are real problems.  Not some media event staged so the poor human has to play where the whole game is stacked against them.

Did the group share what they learned?  Did they devote their remaining years to helping all human kind to live better, safer lives?

Great documentary but this is an example of weak and narrow intelligence. If I were to make the board slightly larger I could still play the game as I can generalise the rules and adapt to change. However the software is only giving the illusion of intelligence and would need to relearn the game from scratch when the board size is changed. That is as the software does not really understand the rules of the game. It is just trained on all possible moves and how to prune the options to increase the probability of winning. That is not really Artificial intelligence the way the term was coined but big data ML with some glorified stats and maths

The power of the AI comes from being able to quantify positive and negative condition states.  A single AI can beat all the games, but that says more about old Atari games.  Score, lives, simple win and fail states are really the bedrock of all the games.  It's more straightforward to give the AI condition states that tell it that it's doing well or badly since they're integrated into the game.  It can learn the game through positive and negative feedback.  That's why a game like GO is so hard for an AI to grasp.  It can't do positive/negative analysis on the moves because the consequence of moves might not be felt until much later in the game.  Although he's claiming his AI is gaining conceptual understanding of the games I don't see any evidence for that.

This is truly alarming. Renee Spitz, in 1945 compared children in a foundling home with children with mothers in prison. Although the children in the foundling home received excellent care which consisted of being changed and receiving food, they were in separate rooms with no contact to adults or other children. They all developed what Spitz called "anaclitic depression"  or "hospitalism"  with the exception of one child whose cot was in the hallway where nurses would pass all day. The children in the prison with their mothers thrived. The children in the foundling home showed retarded growth in every area of function.
Harry & Margaret Harlow, 1950s, U of Wisconsin, separated baby monkeys from their mothers. As a rsult these children became seriously depressed and vicious when in the company of other monkeys later on. Babies in the womb like children after birth need their mothers to grow normally. No amount of artificial hormonal cocktail or sound piped in can duplicate the feeling of being inside a living, breathing, feeling body.
The idea of raising 30,000 humans in  plastic containers is barbaric and would produce, without doubt, vicious unfeeling and deeply disturbed individuals.

Written less than two decades apart, Brave New World and 1984 present very different views about what a runaway technocratic future would look like. They both reflect their author's vision of what a dystopia might look like. A dystopia can be thought of as a society that is designed as a utopia, but functions as the opposite (i.e. something far more terrifying).

In both of these novels, many of the social designs we hold most dear are abolished. The concept of family as we know it is largely greeted with abhorrence. Instead, social institutions revolve largely around the state. Additionally, societies have perhaps become too dependent on what advanced technology has to offer. In any event, a central theme in both works is the importance of control.

In both books, a key method of control is caste. However, there's a catch. There are five major castes in Brave New World, with people conditioned from birth to feel that they can be happy only in their own castes. A Beta, the second-highest caste, may feel that Alphas have to think too hard to have fun, while Gammas have to work too hard. Meanwhile, caste in 1984 is dependent on one's position in the Party. The uninformed masses outside the Party, the Proles, are free to live lives that are little better than those of drones. Meanwhile, Outer Party members are constantly pitted against what the reader would consider to be normal behavior in hopes of gaining access to the luxurious life of the Inner Party. Of course, that opportunity at life in the Inner Party never happens.

Echo life can’t replicate “When pregnant, the cells of the baby migrate into the mothers bloodstream and then circle back into the baby, it’s called “fetal-maternal microchimerism”.⁠

For 41 weeks, the cells circulate and merge backwards and forwards, and after the baby is born, many of these cells stay in the mother’s body, leaving a permanent imprint in the mothers tissues, bones, brain, and skin, and often stay there for decades. Every single child a mother has afterwards will leave a similar imprint on her body, too.

Even if a pregnancy doesn't go to full term or if you have an abortion, these cells still migrate into your bloodstream.

Research has shown that if a mother's heart is injured, fetal cells will rush to the site of the injury and change into different types of cells that specialize in mending the heart.

The baby helps repair the mother, while the mother builds the baby.

How cool is that?

This is often why certain illnesses vanish while pregnant.

It’s incredible how mothers bodies protect the baby at all costs, and the baby protects & rebuilds the mother back - so that the baby can develop safely and survive.

Just so people know, this is a fictional company that does not exist and the technology does not exist to do this. There  has been some research into this concept on other animals, but they have never done a full term of pregnancy artificially. 

They've been able to take an already-conceived lamb and transfer it over to an artificial womb for some number of weeks. But never a full term from conception. 

There is a possibility that this could eventually provide a way to treat extremely premature babies who might otherwise die in the womb. But they are decades away from being able to do this, if it's even possible at all. 

There's nobody currently investing in or building in a facility like this video. It's just science filmmakers' hypothetical idea.

#1 - This video is a concept video. While it is speaking about this thing in the present tense, it does not exist. 

# 2 - It is not clear whether Hashem Al-Ghaili released this video to seek investment or partners to realize EctoLife, or merely to start a conversation. I believe he will be wildly successful in the latter, but I am equally confident he will not be successful in the former. 

#3 - Medical ethics, as it stands today, does not justify or condone this type of human development intervention. Those who cite advancements in care (e.g., artificial placentae) are exaggerating their use in this kind of scenario. 

#4 - In a matter of days, this video will no doubt incite a lot of people to righteous indignation who do not understand #1, #2, #3 above. The videos use of terms like “genetically superior embryo”, “elite package” for genetically engineering the embryo, “factory”, “lab-grown babies”, “growth pods”, “evolution” and terms related to environmental sustainability, seem deliberately intentioned to incense a particular segment of the population. Please do not encourage overreaction by sharing this video as if this exists, or by implying that medical research is is invariably headed in this direction. After the last few years of adamant societal disagreement over the role of medical research and interventions, I fear mankind is not ready to discuss the concepts found in this video objectively and without intense overreaction by those who find this confirmatory of the atrocities they have already convinced themselves are lying ahead.
